Sample mean \(\bar{x} = \frac{1}{n} * \sum_{} x_{i}\)

Sample median \(\bar{x} = x_{(n+1)/2}\) Odd, \(\frac{1}{2}*( x_{n/2} + x_{(n/2)+1})\) Even.

Sample variance \(s^2 = \frac{\sum_{}(x_i - \bar{x})^2}{n-1}\)

Sample standard deviation \(s = \sqrt{s^2}\)

Sample range \(x_{max}-x_{min}\)

Population mean \(\mu = \frac{\sum{}X}{N}\)

Population variance \(\sigma^2 = \frac{\sum_{}(X_i - \mu)^2}{N}\)

Population standard deviation \(\sigma = \sqrt{\sigma^2}\)

\(0 \leq z_{-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\leq P(E) \leq z_{\frac{\alpha}{2}}\leq 1\)

\(Z(Standard Normal Random Varaible) = \frac{x-\bar{x}}{s}\sim \mathcal{N}(0,1)\)

\(P(a \leq X \leq b) = P(\frac{a-\mu}{\sigma}) \leq Z \leq \frac{b-\mu}{\sigma})\)

\(Z(CLT) = \frac{X-\mu}{{\sigma}/{\sqrt{n}}} when \ n \to \infty \ and \ Z \sim \mathcal{N}(0,1)\)
Note: (n>30) and \(\mu =\bar{x}\) and \(\sigma = s\sqrt{n}\) or \(\sigma^2 = s^2 n\)

When sample size increases, sample mean has a larger probability to close to population mean.

\(Z = \frac{(x_1-x_2)-(\mu_1 - \mu_2)}{\sqrt{\sigma_1^2/n_1 + \sigma_2^2/n_2}}\)

Important R functions to generate random numbers, pdf (aka pmf), cdf, and quantiles. The prefixes for these functions are:
- r: random number generation
- d: probability density function or probability mass function
- p: cumulative distribution function
- q: quantiles
